Cloud computing has become the foundation of modern application development by providing scalable, flexible, and cost-effective infrastructure. Organizations hosting applications on traditional on-premises systems often face challenges such as hardware failures, unexpected traffic spikes, manual server management, and downtime. These issues reduce application availability, affect user experience, and increase operational costs. To overcome these challenges, cloud platforms such as Amazon Web Services (AWS) offer automated services that improve system reliability and efficiency.

The project "Self-Healing Infrastructure with Auto Scaling Using AWS" focuses on designing a cloud infrastructure capable of automatically detecting failures, replacing unhealthy servers, and adjusting computing resources according to workload demand. The primary problem addressed by this project is maintaining high availability while minimizing manual intervention during infrastructure failures or sudden increases in user traffic.

The project utilizes various AWS services, including Amazon EC2 for virtual server hosting, Elastic Load Balancer (ELB) for distributing incoming requests across multiple instances, Auto Scaling Group (ASG) for automatically launching or terminating EC2 instances based on demand, and Amazon CloudWatch for continuously monitoring system health and performance metrics. CloudWatch collects metrics such as CPU utilization, memory usage, and instance health, triggering alarms whenever predefined thresholds are exceeded. Based on these alarms, the Auto Scaling Group automatically scales the infrastructure by adding or removing EC2 instances. If an instance becomes unhealthy or fails completely, Auto Scaling replaces it automatically, thereby implementing a self-healing mechanism.

The major objective of this project is to build a highly available, fault-tolerant, and scalable cloud infrastructure that ensures uninterrupted service delivery. By automating infrastructure management, organizations can significantly reduce downtime, improve resource utilization, lower operational costs, and enhance application performance. The project demonstrates how cloud-native services can eliminate many manual administrative tasks while ensuring business continuity even during hardware failures or unexpected traffic surges.

The expected outcome of this project is an AWS-based infrastructure capable of monitoring its own health, recovering automatically from failures, balancing workloads efficiently, and scaling resources dynamically according to user demand. This automated approach not only improves reliability but also optimizes cost by ensuring that resources are used only when necessary. Overall, the project highlights the practical implementation of self-healing cloud architecture and demonstrates how AWS services can be integrated to build resilient and efficient enterprise applications.
